{{BLP sources|date=July 2015}}

'''Gautam Bhadra''' is a  [[historian]] of [[South Asia]] and was a member of the erstwhile [[Subaltern Studies]] collective. Bhadra was born in [[Kolkata]] in 1948. He obtained education at [[Presidency University, Kolkata|Presidency College]], Jadavpur University and [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]].<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://chhatimbooks.com/gautam-bhadra.html  | title = Gautam Bhadra, Author Profile | author = Chhatim Books}}</ref> He started teaching at the Department of History, University of Calcutta and continued there for more than 15 years. After that, he became the professor of history at Centre for Studies in Social Sciences, Calcutta (1996-2010). He was the first Tagore National Fellow at the [[National Library of India|National Library]] in Kolkata.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.nationallibrary.gov.in/FromDirector.htm | title = Message from the Director General | author = National Library}}</ref> Currently he is Honorary Professor at the Centre for Studies in Social Sciences (Jadunath Bhavan Museum and Resource Centre).

==Awards and honours==

In 2011, Bhadra was conferred with the prestigious Bengali literary award, [[Ananda Puraskar]], for his book 'Nyara Bot-tolaye Jai Ko-bar?'<ref>{{cite web |url = http://twocircles.net/2011apr30/historian_gautam_bhadra_awarded_bengali_literary_prize.html#.VTn-oSGqqko | title = Historian Gautam Bhadra awarded Bengali literary prize | author = TwoCircles.net}}</ref>

