{{Infobox civil conflict | title = Husino rebellion | partof = | image = | caption = | date = 21–28 December 1920 | place = Husino, [[Tuzla]], [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] | coordinates = | causes = | goals = | methods = | status = | result = | side1 = Miners led by Juro Kerošević | side2 = Army of the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes | leadfigures1 = | leadfigures2 = | howmany1 = 7,000 | howmany2 = two [[battalion]]s, 69 gendarmerie | casualties1 = | casualties2 = | fatalities = 7 | injuries = | arrests = {{circa|400}} | detentions = | charged = | fined = | casualties_label = | notes = }}
'''Husino rebellion''' ({{lang-sh|Husinska buna}}, Хусинска буна){{Cref2|a}} was a short-lived miners strike and armed rebellion against industrial slavery in the newly established [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]]. 7,000 miners from [[Tuzla]], [[Breza, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Breza]] and [[Zenica]] in central [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]], participated in the strike in the village of Husino in Tuzla. When the local government tried to force the miners back to work, they resisted with firearms and the uprising was put down with great violence. Seven workers were killed and four-hundred arrested. The uprising was put down, but its memory was preserved as part of Tuzla’s anti-authoritarian legacy.
The rebellion has been called one of the most important historical events in Yugoslavia and has remained an example of class struggle against injustice and oppression.
==Event== A miners' strike began on 21 December 1920 in Husino when the miners requested a rise of wages of 30-45% to counter the gallop inflation which had paralyzed the economy of the [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] (+60% between August and December 1920). Even with threats in the event of refusal of the authorities, the miners began a general strike. This very badly accommodated by the authorities who took radical measures to counter it. On the night of 27–28 December 1920, they sent a troop of 19 [[gendarmerie]] and police officers, who were ordered to evacuate the houses of the strikers in order to capture them and to counterbalance them, to Husino, which was then regarded as general headquarter of the strike movement.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
The main actors of the strike were Jure Kerošević (Guja), Osman Đulović (Topčo), Mujo Đulović (Mujko), Karlo Železnik, Ivan Brcun, Franjo Marić, Marko Fidler, Bozo Mrkić, Simo Topalović, Mijo Tomić.
The 7,000 miners, armed with simple stones and pickaxes, quickly decimated the gendarmes and police officers, which caused the anger of the authorities who sent two battalions of the army as well as heavy artillery and 50 gendarmes that same evening. Vis-à-vis the army, the miners had only one choice: to surrender and give up their requirements. The rebellion was choked in blood by the Yugoslav government and the miners and their families' homes were confiscated, women were raped, over 400 people were arrested and some were [[Expatriate|expatriated]].{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
Thirteen months later, the revolt got an epilogue in a trial conducted in Tuzla in January–February 1922. The indictment charged the {{circa|350}} miners, including the leader of the uprising, Juro Kerošević, who was originally sentenced to death by hanging for allegedly killing [[gendarmerie]] officers. However, under pressure from domestic and international publicity the penalty was commuted to 20 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slobodnaevropa.org/content/zaboravljene-vrijednosti-dan-rudara-i-husinska-buna/24805508.html|title=Zaboravljene vrijednosti: Dan rudara i Husinska buna|publisher=Slobodna Evropa|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://novovrijeme.ba/husinska-buna-u-vremenu-tranzicije/|title=Husinska buna u vremenu tranzicije|publisher=Novo vrijeme|date=2 February 2013|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> 32 miners were sentenced to death and 10 other miners were penalized with prison time ranging from 1–15 months.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
==Aftermath and legacy== The rebellion has been called one of the most important historical events in the [[former Yugoslavia]] and has remained an example of class struggle against injustice and oppression.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abrasmedia.info/content/husinska-buna-dan-rudara-bosne-i-hercegovine-video|title=Husinska buna - Dan rudara Bosne i Hercegovine|publisher=Abras Media||accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfQEAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA125|title=Bosnian Muslims in the Second World War|p=125|publisher=|date=1 February 2014|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref>
The [[steles]] of the victims installed in the municipal park of Husino testify still today to that dark time in the recent history of the village. A monument to memorialize the Husino miners was erected in 1956, showing a miner dropping his pick for a rifle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/15/world/europe/roots-of-bosnian-protests-lie-in-peace-accords-of-1995.html?hpw&rref=world|title=Roots of Bosnian Protests Lie in Peace Accords of 1995|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|date=14 February 2014|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> In [[SFR Yugoslavia]], 21 December was celebrated as ''Miners' Day'' throughout the country, because of the Husino Uprising. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhreporter.ba/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4561:foto-21-decembar-dan-rudara&catid=30:bh&Itemid=168|title=21. decembar - Dan rudara|publisher=BH Reporter|date=21 December 2013|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtvslon.ba/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=16654:rudari-bih-danas-slave-svoj-dan&catid=1:vijesti&Itemid=5|title=Rudari BiH danas slave svoj dan|publisher=RTV Slon|date=21 December 2013|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.depo.ba/vijest/26947|title=Sjećanje na Husinsku bunu, najveću pobunu bosanskih rudara|publisher=depo|date=21 December 2010|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref>
During the [[Bosnian War]] (1992–95), a boot camp in Tuzla was named ''Husinska buna''.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
In February 2014, multiple Bosnian newspapers including ''[[Oslobođenje]]'' called the [[2014 unrest in Bosnia and Herzegovina]], the "new Husino Uprising".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oslobodjenje.ba/vijesti/bih/bosansko-proljece-pocela-je-nova-husinska-buna |title=Bosansko proljeće: Počela je nova Husinska buna |publisher=Oslobođenje |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=15 February 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223011529/http://www.oslobodjenje.ba/vijesti/bih/bosansko-proljece-pocela-je-nova-husinska-buna |archivedate=23 February 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=1172334|title=Tuzlanska «nova Husinjska buna»|publisher=Vreme|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/komentari.php?nav_id=809277|title=Mediji u BiH: Nova Husinska buna|publisher=b92|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/svijet/314276/Pocela-je-nova-Husinska-buna.html|title='Počela je nova Husinska buna'|publisher=TPortal|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref>
==In popular culture== A folk song called ''Konjuh planinom'' (''[[Konjuh (mountain)|Konjuh]] Mountain'') was inspired by the uprising in the Husino village. It was first sung by Pejo Marković, who was killed in 1944 during World War II. Televizija Sarajevo produced a television film about the Husino Uprising called ''Husinska buna'' (''Husino Rebellion'', 1980).{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
==See also== *[[Cazin rebellion]] *[[Rebellions in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]
==Annotations== {{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}} {{Cnote2|a|Usually called ''Husinska buna'' in Bosnian, the event has been referred to in English as "Husino rebellion", ''Husino Uprising'', "Husino Revolt", ''Uprising of Husino Village'', or the ''Husino Miner's Revolt''.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} The name of the village Husino is attributed to either a man named Huso, an Ottoman who reigned on the area in the 15th century, or the name could derive from the word ''husa'', which is an old Slavic word meaning ''trap'' or ''ambush''.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} }} {{Cnote2 End}}
